  footnotes: []
english:
  title: Dawn Watch
  author: Park Eun
  language: eng
  text: |-
    Stars descend toward the sea at break of dawn,
    High in the tower, cold assails the wanderer.
    Beyond this frame, heaven and earth stretch vast—
    Sitting here, drum and horn sound out their call.

    Distant mountains blur like mist before my eyes,
    Loud bird-song awakens me to spring's arrival.
    Last night's drunken haze must surely lift,
    Yet idly still, poetry's allure holds sway.
  footnotes:
    - The 'drum and horn' (고각) refer to military instruments often sounded at dawn in traditional East Asian fortified cities, grounding the speaker's solitary moment in a world of human activity.
    - The poem moves from cosmic observation to intimate self-awareness, suggesting how the vastness of nature can paradoxically dissolve the poet's sense of isolation.
